# Mindset Theory: Priority-Based Mind Mapping

The premise of this mental model is that we can better understand individuals, groups, institutions, and behavior by observing and mapping their priorities.

This can be done internally through intuition and simple heuristics, or through some kind of computational model capable of organizing larger amounts of information.

Every living system has to make decisions. Those decisions contain tradeoffs and are ultimately tied to identity. By identifying the geometry of a system’s priorities, we can derive an archetypal representation of that priority structure.

> **A mindset is a geometry of priorities. Situations act as attractors, drawing the system into recurring configurations within that geometry. These configurations can be represented as archetypal masks.**

This is my attempt to map those structures as I have observed and intuited them through lived experience. It draws from the work of many great thinkers, scientists, philosophers, and mystics.

By compressing these structures into a simplified system, we can create a practical map that works with the mind’s natural ability to recognize patterns. Someone can use it to make quick assessments of another person’s priority structure, better anticipate their behavior, or reflect upon their own archetypes: the masks they wear and the figures they unconsciously become inside their own stories.

The other files will go into greater detail about each part of the model. My intention is to work through it piece by piece until it becomes something useful.

## A Brief Overview

The model begins with three main priority domains:

| Domain        | Symbolic origin | Masculine anchor | Feminine anchor |
| ------------- | --------------- | ---------------- | --------------- |
| **Value**     | Spirit          | Dignity          | Recognition     |
| **Stability** | Nervous system  | Security         | Harmony         |
| **Resources** | Body            | Acquisition      | Comfort         |

Each domain represents a much larger field of priorities.

To simplify and compress the information inside those fields, I divided them around masculine and feminine semantic anchors in the spiritual sense.

Masculine priorities are often associated with men, but they are present in both men and women. Feminine priorities are also present in both. Their arrangement differs between individuals, and different situations draw people toward different regions of their existing priority structure.

The masculine and feminine symbols create an intuitive structure that people can understand because these patterns are already familiar to us and have deep roots in spiritual traditions.

The semantic points I chose create a polarized field between spiritually masculine and feminine qualities. These points are placeholders inside a much larger information space.

I tried to strip human needs down toward their base compulsions. The deeper layers of motivation exist as shapes somewhere around, between, and across those anchor points: a field of motives, values, fears, needs, and desires whose attributes suggest a larger priority structure.

```text
              ·        ·        ·
        ·         DIGNITY             ·
             ·         ·
                       ·      RECOGNITION
          ·        ·          ·
```

With **Value**, the spiritual priority domain, we have the masculine anchor of **Dignity** and the feminine anchor of **Recognition**.

These words carry layers of meaning, but they are constrained by their role as priorities. Dignity here means Dignity as something prioritized. Recognition means Recognition as something prioritized. Other related priorities cluster around them according to their similarity and relationship to the wider field.

The real structure is far more complex than six words. The purpose of the six words is to give the human mind something it can recognize, remember, and use.

PBMM maps priority structures and archetypal masks.

Its relevance lies in what motivates people, what drives them, what they defend, what they sacrifice, and how these signals form coherent shapes.

Situations act as attractors within that geometry. A creative situation may draw out one configuration. Conflict may draw out another. Responsibility, intimacy, opportunity, danger, and isolation each call forth different regions already present within the system.

When those configurations recur, they form clusters.

When those clusters become coherent enough to recognize, they take archetypal form.

The six priority anchors create a three-by-three grid. Each pairing can be ordered in two directions, producing eighteen archetypal configurations.

```text
        3 MASCULINE ANCHORS
                  ×
        3 FEMININE ANCHORS
                  =
            9 PAIRINGS

            9 PAIRINGS
                  ×
        2 PRIORITY ORDERS
                  =
        18 ARCHETYPAL MASKS
```

Archetypes are related to the masks we wear and the figures we unconsciously see ourselves as inside our stories.

An archetype compresses a priority structure into a form the mind can grasp.

Archetypes can carry many names. I chose names that align with parallel systems in mythology, psychology, philosophy, metaphysics, and esoteric practice. I prefer archetypes that inspire wonder and carry enough symbolic depth that people can feel their meaning intuitively.

The names may change as the map develops and better landmarks are discovered.

I am still discovering where this leads, but I believe it is worthwhile to map and name these structures from first principles.

By understanding ourselves and each other more clearly, we can recognize the hidden structures beneath our differences. We can see the masks we wear, the stories they place us inside, and the priorities shaping our movement through the world.

Perhaps this becomes a practical system for understanding individuals, groups, institutions, and cultures.

Perhaps it remains a personal process.

We shall see.




